node.text:
Let’s talk ABGs⁣
⁣
💉ABG = arterial blood gas💉⁣
⁣
An ABG test measures the acidity/pH and the levels of oxygen & carbon dioxide from an artery⁣
⁣
Why would we test this? 🤔⁣
To assess the function of the pt’s lungs and how well they are able to move O2 into the blood and remove CO2⁣
⁣
✅NORMAL PH: 7.35-7.45⁣
If pH is less than 7.35 = acidosis⁣
If pH is greater than 7.45 = alkalosis⁣
⁣
✅NORMAL CO2: 35-45⁣
The CO2 reading tells you if the problem is a respiratory issue or not⁣
⁣
✅NORMAL HCO3/BICARB: 22-26⁣
The bicarb reading tells you if the problem is a metabolic issue or not⁣
⁣
👉🏼ANALYZING ABGS:⁣
1. Is pH acidic or alkalodic? If <7.35 = acidosis, if >7.45 = alkalosis⁣
2. Is the problem Respiratory or Metabolic? In respiratory disorders, the pH and PaCO2 change in opposite directions (high pH, low CO2; low pH, high CO2). In metabolic disorders the pH and PaCO2 change in the same direction (high pH, high HCO3; low pH, low HCO3). ROME (respiratory = opposite, metabolic = equal)⁣
3. Compensation? Usually, compensation does not return the pH to normal (7.35 – 7.45). No compensation = one of CO2 or bicarb is normal. Full compensation = pH is normal⁣
⁣

Here’s an NG tube tip for every nursing student and new grad 👌🏼⁣
⁣
LIKE & SAVE THIS VID FOR FUTURE REFERENCE 🥰

Rundown of my favourite @wearfigs styles, my sizing/recommendations, and a quick Q+A because I get asked about them almost daily!⁣
⁣
If you don’t want to watch the full video:⁣
⁣
My coupon code➡️ figsxbarbara⁣
⁣
👚 Fave styles = Catarina top, Yola bottoms, Zamora Jogger bottoms⁣
⁣
👩🏽‍⚕️ My sizing = I’m about 5’6 + 113 lbs, normally wear an XS/0/24 or 25. I wear a size XXS in my scrubs (tips & bottoms). I could probably get away with sizing up to an XS in the Yola bottoms but otherwise, the XXS in the top + jogger bottom fit great⁣
⁣
❓Do they shrink with wash? No⁣
❓If I’m in between sizes, what should I do? Personally, I’d choose the larger size.. nothing worse than working 12 hrs in something too tight⁣
❓Shipping to Canada? Yep!! All of the duties + shipping are shown to you before you pay - there’s no surprise at your doorstep. And yes, the company is working on lowering this cost for us Canadians!⁣
❓Do they last? Yep, I’ve been wearing some pairs for over 2.5 years now :)⁣

Post-shift routine:⁣
 ⁣
— Shower⁣
— Give myself a ‘body mask’ with the @cetaphilcanada moisturizing cream (kind of like a hair mask, but for your body)⁣
— Eat, hop into bed, and relax⁣
 ⁣
If any of you have worked in the hospital, you know how drying the air is (don’t ask me why... but it is). Coming home from a shift, I feel like my skin is screaming for some moisture which is why I’ve started to lather on the @cetaphilcanada moisturizing cream post-shower. I wake up the next morning and it’s as if I never even worked in the hospital for 12 hours the day before.⁣
 ⁣
If any of you also suffer from really dry skin post-shift, you need to try this method out!! #ad⁣
 ⁣
#bareallwithcetaphil #mycetaphilskin #cetaphilcanada

node.text:
🫀ACLS drug review🫀⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣
EPINEPHRINE ➖ vasopressor⁣⁣⁣⁣
Used for 👉🏼 VF/Pulseless VT; Asystole/PEA; Symptomatic Bradycardia⁣⁣⁣⁣
D O S E = 1mg IV/IO q3-5min⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣
AMIODARONE ➖ antiarrhythmic ⁣⁣⁣⁣
Used for 👉🏼 VF/Pulseless VT; recurrent, hemodynamically unstable VT⁣⁣⁣⁣
D O S E = 300 mg IV/IO push; second dose 150 mg IV/IO push⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣
ATROPINE ➖ Anticholinergic⁣⁣⁣⁣
Used for 👉🏼 Bradycardia⁣⁣⁣⁣
D O S E = 1 mg IV bolus; q3-5mon, max 3 mg⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣
MAGNESIUM SULFATE ➖ Antiarrhythmic, Electrolyte⁣⁣⁣⁣
Used to 👉🏼 terminate or prevent recurrent VT associated with Torsades de Pointes⁣⁣⁣⁣
D O S E = 1-2 g diluted in 10 ml D5W IV push⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣⁣
ADENOSINE ➖ Antiarrhythmic⁣⁣⁣⁣
Used for 👉🏼 when vagal maneuvers fail to terminate: stable narrow-complex SVT and VT⁣⁣⁣
D O S E = 6 mg RAPID IV push. Don’t forget 20 ml IV flush and elevation of extremity after administration⁣⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣
SODIUM BICARB ➖ Alkalinizing agent⁣⁣⁣
Used for 👉🏼 correcting metabolic acidosis (acid wastes build up in the body after the heart stops beating)⁣⁣⁣
D O S E =  1 mEq/kg IV push in a dose of 50ml, D5W solution⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣⁣
⁣⁣
📸: @pagethepa

node.text:
Let’s talk 👉🏼 EF⁣
⁣
Ejection fraction = EF⁣
⁣
What is EF?⁣
It refers to how well your LEFT VENTRICLE is PUMPING blood with each contraction/heart beat (when we talk about EF, we can be talking about either R or L ventricle.. most cases, it’s the L ventricle we are referring to!)⁣
Remember — left ventricle provides 🩸oxygenated blood🩸 to your entire body⁣
⁣
Usually EF is measured during an echocardiogram (this is basically an ultrasound of the heart)⁣
⁣
EF is expressed as a % .. a lower than normal EF is a sign of heart failure⁣
⁣
🫀NORMAL EF = 55-70%🫀⁣
Heart’s pumping ability — normal⁣
(Let’s say someone has an EF of 70%.. this means 70% of the total amount of blood in the L ventricle is pumped out with every contraction/heart beat)⁣
⁣
🫀MILD DYSFUNCTION; EF = 40-54%🫀⁣
Less blood pumped from the L ventricle = less oxygenated blood is available to the body!⁣
Pt may not have symptoms at this point⁣
⁣
🫀MODERATEL DYSFUNCTION; EF = 30-39%🫀⁣
⁣
🫀SEVERE DYSFUNCTION; EF = <30%🫀⁣
⁣
Common S/S of heart failure = SOB, fatigue, edema to the ankles & legs, weight gain, dry cough⁣
⁣
⁣
⁣

node.text:
The other day I was asked how much $ I made as an RN - I shared this chart (it can be found on my union’s website) and was flooded with messages saying how little pay this is compared to other places (e.g. California)⁣
⁣
100% - I think the pay for RNs should be raised, but I also understand that I have a union protecting me/backing me up and I also have free healthcare in Ontario.. this can’t be said for many nurses in the US ⁣
⁣
Considering I wear so many different ‘hats’ as a nurse and I work tirelessly to provide the safest & most compassionate care to my patients - I definitely hope to see some kind of pay increase in the coming years..⁣
⁣
Where do you live & what is the average pay (include the # of years youve been working)?? I’m curious to see how big a difference there is!🤔⁣
⁣
⁣

Transitioning from a nursing student to a nurse — here’s one thing you’ll have to learn during your first few months on the floor:⁣
⁣
— time management — ⁣
you’ll be handling a full patient load, getting calls from family members, admitting new patients, dealing with a critical lab result, paging doctors, processing orders, answering call lights, and so much more.. it can be overwhelming trying to manage this all, but with time/practice, you’ll get the hang of it (and you’ll know what to prioritize versus what can wait until later)⁣
⁣
some tips:⁣
👉🏼Write out a to-do list so you can try to plan out your day as best as you can⁣
👉🏼If you have some free time in the morning, chart!! I chart my vitals as soon as I finish taking them, that way I know I have at least some sort of documentation done (and docs can view them in the morning)⁣
👉🏼Ask for help if you’re drowning - this job requires teamwork!⁣
👉🏼Use your resources; unit clerk, PT, educators, etc. .. just because you can handle juggling everything on your own doesn’t mean you should! Give yourself a break!⁣

node.text:
Change of shift report ⤵️⁣
⁣
Firstly, shift report should be given at the patient’s bedside so the oncoming nurse can visually assess the patient and confirm the pt’s general status, any continuous IVs running, and safety of the environment⁣
⁣
Points to include while giving report:⁣
👩🏽‍⚕️ Patients name, age, diagnosis, code status, and relevant PMHx⁣
👩🏽‍⚕️Are vital signs stable - if not, note which VS are abnormal and what you did to intervene. You can also include if the pt is on any supplemental O2 here⁣
👩🏽‍⚕️ Neuro - are they A&O x 3? If not, is this a change from baseline? You can also note any delirium or sundowning⁣
👩🏽‍⚕️ Cardiorespiratory - any arrhythmias, chest pain, S/S of heart failure, dyspnea, adventitious lung sounds, etc⁣
👩🏽‍⚕️ GI/GU - is the pt continent? Does the pt have a Foley, any orders for bladder scanning, are they using the toilet, bedside commode, urinal, etc. Has the pt had any BMs during your shift - are they constipated or have they been have +++ BMs⁣
👩🏽‍⚕️ MSK - how does the patient ambulate⁣
👩🏽‍⚕️Integumentary - note any wounds or dressing changes that need to be done⁣
👩🏽‍⚕️ Lines - note any saline locks, continuous IV fluids or medication infusions, any dialysis lines, drain lines, tube feeds lines, etc⁣
👩🏽‍⚕️ Intake - let the oncoming nurse know how the pt takes their medications (whole, crushed, one at a time, etc), if there are any concerns with their nutritional intake, and if they’re on a specific diet - e.g NPO for morning surgery, thickened fluids only, etc⁣
👩🏽‍⚕️ Labs - any critical labs from your shift⁣
👩🏽‍⚕️ Pending tests and consults - what tests or consultations are pending, when are they scheduled for, is there any prep needed for a diagnostic test, etc⁣
👩🏽‍⚕️ Discharge issues - what’s holding the patient from being discharged home⁣

MED MONDAY - DIGOXIN⠀⁣
Also known as — Lanoxin ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⁣
⁣
What is it: an antidysrhythmic and inotropic agent ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⁣
⁣
❓What is an inotropic agent ➡️ it’s a medicine that changes the heart’s force of contraction⁣
With digoxin we have a ➕positive➕ inotropic effect: the heart’s contractions strengthen = resulting in a decreased heart rate (the heart is able to pump more effectively, so less beats per minute are needed) ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⁣
⁣
💊What is digoxin used for: atrial fibrillation, atrial flutter, and heart failure⁣
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⁣
How does it work: digoxin causes increased availability of intracellular calcium in the myocardium and conduction system. Inotropy is then increased = more forceful contractions and decreased HR ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⁣
⁣
👩🏽‍⚕️Adverse effects: dizziness, headache, diarrhea, nausea⁣
⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⁣
💉Administration: digoxin can be given PO or IV ⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⠀⁣
⁣
☝🏼REMEMBER:⁣
Check your patient’s HR before administration⁣
In the geriatric population, lean body weight should be used to calculate the dose⁣
There is a very narrow margin between effective therapeutic and toxic dosages (therapeutic range: 0.5-2 ng/mL; target 0.5-1 ng/mL; toxic range, >2.5 ng/mL)⁣

NCLEX NEED-TO-KNOWS:⁣
⁣
Therapeutic drug levels⤵️⁣
➖Digoxin: 0.5–2.0 ng/ml⁣
➖Lithium: 0.8–1.5 mEq/L⁣
➖Dilantin: 10–20 mcg/dL⁣
➖Theophylline: 10–20 mcg/dL⁣
⁣
Maternity normals⤵️⁣
➖FHR: 120–160 BPM.⁣
➖Variability: 6–10 BPM.⁣
➖Contractions: normal frequency 2–5 minutes apart; normal duration < 90 sec.; intensity < 100 mm/hg.⁣
➖Amniotic fluid: 500–1200 ml (nitrozine urine-litmus paper green/amniotic fluid-litmus paper blue)⁣
➖Apgar scoring: A = appearance, P = pulses, G = grimace, A = activity, R = reflexes (Done at 1 and 5 minutes with a score of 0 for absent, 1 for decreased, and 2 for strongly positive.)⁣
➖AVA: The umbilical cord has two arteries and one vein. (Arteries carry deoxygenated blood. The vein carries oxygenated blood.)⁣
⁣
Rule of nines for calculating TBSA for burns⤵️⁣
➖Head = 9%⁣
➖Arms = 18% (9% each)⁣
➖Back = 18%⁣
➖Legs = 36% (18% each)⁣
➖Genitalia = 1%⁣
⁣
Five Ps of fractures and compartment syndrome— These are symptoms of fractures and compartment syndrome⤵️⁣
➖Pain⁣
➖Pallor⁣
➖Pulselessness⁣
➖Paresthesia⁣
➖Polar (cold)⁣
⁣
Addison’s versus Cushing’s⤵️⁣
➖Treatment for the pt with Addison’s: increase sodium intake; medications include cortisone preparations.⁣
➖Treatment for the pt with Cushing’s: restrict sodium; observe for signs of infection.
